Even with the officials of native birth the arch- bishop had some difficulty in maintaining friendly relations, His chancellor, William Wickwane‚ who afterwards succeeded him in the archbishopriC‚ - accused him of encroaching upon his rights and robbing him of certain fees pertaining to his office (No. ¹4 5). With the Archdeacon of Cleveland, who was a foreigner, as is mentioned above, it was not to be expected that his relations would be cordial. According to the archbishop’s statement (No. 351), the archdeacon treated him very ungrate- fully. He had always been the archdeacon's friend, and he was astonished to find him accusing him to the Pope. Although this friction existed between them, the archbishop attached great weight to the archdeacon’s opinion, and in one case, wrote a special letter to ask his advice on a matter of difficulty (N ο. 650). The most troublesome dignitary with whom Giffard had to deal was the Archdeacon of Nottingham, Thomas de Wyten, who had to be publicly admonished to be obedient (No, 43).
